So she plays her lethally capricious son Nero (William Robinson, excellent) off against stepson Britannicus (Nathaniel Curtis from It's A Sin) and it's a power play that can only end in blood. On a simple set of chairs and a huge hanging depicting Romulus and Remus, the small cast battles it out for dominion in a production that has one foot in Senecan tragedy and the other in Dynasty. Saba's power-dressed-to-kill Agrippina is terrific as she wields matriarchal authority like a lightsaber. Although Racine's drama is essentially static, director Atri Bannerjee delivers a powerhouse production by introducing elements of physical theatre.